## 2. Outer loop — attitude control

### 2.1 Block diagram with feedback paths

```
                                              ┌───────────────────────────────────┐
                                              │       OUTER LOOP — ATTITUDE       │
                                              │                                    │
   q_d ───────────────────────►( Σ_e )───► eq ──►[ P (per-axis) ]────►( Σ )─────► ω_sp
                                  ▲                                       ▲
                              (−) │                                       │
                                  │                                       │
                                  │                                  [ −D · ω ]   ← KW fork addition
                                  │                                       ▲
                                  │                                       │
                                  │                              ┌────────┴──────────────┐
                                  │                              │  rate feedback ω      │
                                  │                              │  vehicle_angular_     │
                                  │                              │   velocity.xyz        │
                                  │                              └───────────────────────┘
                                  │
                                  │                                       │
                                  │                          [ yaw FF: q⁻¹·dcm_z · ψ̇_FF ]
                                  │                          (yaw axis only, line 102-104)
                                  │                                       ▲
                                  │                                       │
                                  │                                       │ uses q feedback too
                                  │                              ┌────────┴──────────────┐
                                  │                              │  q from EKF2          │
                                  │                              │  vehicle_attitude.q   │
                                  │                              └───────────────────────┘
                                  │
                                  │   ATTITUDE FEEDBACK PATH (primary)
                                  │   ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
                                  │
                                  └────── q (from EKF2: vehicle_attitude.q) ◄──── [ PLANT ]
                                                                                  (inner loop
                                                                                  + allocator
                                                                                  + motors
                                                                                  + airframe
                                                                                  + IMU
                                                                                  + EKF2)
   Notes:
   • The error junction is a quaternion product, not a subtraction:
        qe = q⁻¹ · qd_blended
        eq = 2·imag(qe.canonical())     ← axis-angle error vector (3D)
     The "Σ_e" symbol denotes this attitude-error operation per axis.

   • qd_blended is the yaw-deprioritized desired attitude (line 60-81):
        Quatf qd_red(e_z, e_z_d);                       // align thrust axis only
        qd = qd_red * Quatf(cos(yaw_w·acos(...)),       // blend with full qd
                            0, 0, sin(yaw_w·asin(...))) //   weighted by MC_YAW_WEIGHT

   • The output ω_sp is clipped per-axis to ±MC_*RATE_MAX before publication.
```

### 2.2 Equation (per axis i ∈ {φ, θ, ψ})

```
    eq[i]   = 2·imag( q⁻¹ · qd_blended )[i]                    ← attitude error (rad)
    ω_sp[i] = P[i] · eq[i]  −  D[i] · ω_meas[i]                ← P + D
                            + (q⁻¹·dcm_z · ψ̇_FF)[i]            ← yaw FF (yaw axis only)
    ω_sp[i] = clip( ω_sp[i], ±rate_max[i] )
```

### 2.3 Per-channel breakdown

| | **Roll (φ)** | **Pitch (θ)** | **Yaw (ψ)** |
|---|---|---|---|
| Setpoint origin (Stabilize) | stick → tilt magnitude+direction → `q_sp_rp` (line 145-171) | same coupled tilt path | stick → world yaw rate, integrated to absolute yaw (line 117-129) |
| Attitude feedback | `vehicle_attitude.q` (EKF2 ~100 Hz) | same | same |
| Rate feedback (for D term) | `vehicle_angular_velocity.xyz[0]` | `.xyz[1]` | `.xyz[2]` |
| **P** | `MC_ROLL_P` = 6.5 | `MC_PITCH_P` = 6.5 | `MC_YAW_P` = 2.8 |
| **D** (KW fork) | `MC_ROLL_D` = 0.0 | `MC_PITCH_D` = 0.0 | `MC_YAW_D` = 0.0 |
| Yaw weight | — | — | `MC_YAW_WEIGHT` = 0.4 |
| Output clip | `MC_ROLLRATE_MAX` = 220°/s | `MC_PITCHRATE_MAX` = 220°/s | `MC_YAWRATE_MAX` = 200°/s |
| Yaw FF source | — | — | `vehicle_attitude_setpoint.yaw_sp_move_rate` |
| Output field | `vehicle_rates_setpoint.roll` | `.pitch` | `.yaw` |

### 2.4 Where the feedback enters

- **Attitude `q`** is subscribed via a uORB callback work-item on `vehicle_attitude` (`mc_att_control.hpp:108`). Every update triggers a `Run()` cycle. Inside `Run()` (line 217-218), the latest `vehicle_angular_velocity` is also copied. Both are passed to `AttitudeControl::update(q, rates)` at line 303.
- **Rate `ω`** is used at line 92 of `AttitudeControl.cpp` (`rate_setpoint_d = -rates.emult(_derivative_gain)`) for the D-term, and at line 103 to rotate `_yawspeed_setpoint` from world frame to body frame.

