## 5. KnightWerx fork — relevant deviations

### 5.1 Attitude D term (commit `76328d9640`, 2024-09-10)

The fork adds derivative control to the outer (attitude) loop. Without this commit, the outer loop is pure P + yaw-FF; with it, the outer loop is P + D + yaw-FF.

Files modified:
- `src/modules/mc_att_control/AttitudeControl/AttitudeControl.{cpp,hpp}` — `update()` now takes `rates`; `_derivative_gain` member added.
- `src/modules/mc_att_control/mc_att_control.hpp` — derivative-gain plumbing.
- `src/modules/mc_att_control/mc_att_control_main.cpp:303` — `rates` passed in.
- `src/modules/mc_att_control/mc_att_control_params.c` — `MC_ROLL_D`, `MC_PITCH_D`, `MC_YAW_D` (all default 0.0).

With params at 0.0, behavior is identical to upstream. Any non-zero value enables the rate-feedback D path shown in section 2.1.

### 5.2 Heading-good-for-control bypass

A comment in `mc_att_control_main.cpp` near line 331 disables a yaw-setpoint reset that would otherwise fire on EKF heading-quality drops. Practical effect for Stabilize: yaw setpoints are not snapped during heading resets.

### 5.3 Yaw weight rescaling — subtle interaction with the new D term

`setProportionalGain()` divides yaw P by `_yaw_w` (line 51 of `AttitudeControl.cpp`) so that `MC_YAW_P` is the effective end-to-end yaw gain regardless of `MC_YAW_WEIGHT`. The new **D gain is not rescaled the same way** — so if you set `MC_YAW_D > 0` and then change `MC_YAW_WEIGHT`, the yaw P and yaw D will scale differently. Worth knowing when tuning.

### 5.4 Rate controller — no fork divergence

`git log hotfix..origin/dev` on `src/modules/mc_rate_control/` and `src/lib/rate_control/` returns nothing. The inner loop in this checkout is byte-identical to upstream `dev`. The dormant anti-windup is upstream behavior, not a local change.

